array.string: Valentina Tereshkova first woman in space
The first woman in space was a Soviet cosmonaut. Valentina Tereshkova launched with the Vostok 6 mission
Aleksei Leonov: first person to walk in space.
Tethered to his spaceship by a 4.8m (16ft) cable, the Russian floated above the Earth for 12 minutes.
Luna 9 makes the first landing on the Moon.
USSR's Luna 9: The lander had a mass of 99 kilograms (218 lb). It used a landing bag to survive the impact speed of 22 kilometres per hour (14 mph).
Apollo 11 was the spaceflight that first landed humans on the Moon. Armstrong became the first person to step onto the lunar surface.
Venera 7 is first on another planet (Venus).
Venera 7 was a Soviet spacecraft. When it landed on the Venusian surface , it became the first spacecraft to soft land on another planet and first to transmit data from there back to Earth.
Salyut 1 was the first space station of any kind, launched into low Earth orbit by the Soviet Union.
